<DOC><DOCNO> ZF32-214-162 </DOCNO><DOCID>10 518 196</DOCID><JOURNAL>Today's Office  March 1991 v25 n10 p20(3).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Building a LAN-based office.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Wohl, Amy D.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Many companies can benefit from installing local area networks(LAN) but do not know how to make the transition from standalonemicrocomputers.andP;  Companies can buy everything from one vendor, orbuy from a systems integrator, or integrate the different piecesof equipment necessary using company resources.andP;  Elements thatneed to be integrated include the physical LAN, including cables,connectors, and other hardware; the LAN operating system, onenetwork server, one workstation for each user, and officeapplication software.andP;  Setting up a network for a Macintosh systemis easy, since it is equipped with a built-in LAN connector.andO;However, there are some situations where the use of a professionalis appropriate.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Local Area NetworksBusiness PlanningMicrocomputersIntegrated Office SystemsComputer Systems IntegratorsNetwork Operating SystemsApplications.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>